          <h3>Concerns about novel coronavirus disease (COVID-19)</h3>
          <p class="fst-italic">
            The virus that causes coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) has not been shown to be transmitted through blood
            transfusions. However, the US Food and Drug Administration suggests that people who want to donate blood
            wait at least 10 days after a positive COVID-19 diagnostic test without symptoms, or at least 10 days after
            the symptoms of COVID-19 have completely resolved.

            Those found to have antibodies to the COVID-19 virus but who have not undergone a diagnostic test and never
            developed symptoms can donate without the need for a waiting period or a diagnostic test before donating.
          </p>
          <p>
            If you get a non-cloned, inactivated, or mRNA-based COVID-19 vaccine, you can donate blood without a waiting
            period. However, if a live-attenuated COVID-19 vaccine is available and you received it, wait 14 days after
            the vaccine before donating blood. And if you're not sure what kind of vaccine you've had, wait 14 days
            before donating blood.
          </p>
        </div>
