          <h3>during the procedure</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><i class="bi bi-check"></i>You will lie or sit in a comfortable chair that has an adjustable back and
              footrest with your arm extended on the armrest. If you prefer to use a specific arm or vein, make it clear
              to the person drawing the blood sample. A blood pressure cuff or tourniquet will be wrapped around your
              upper arm so that the veins fill with more blood. This also makes it easier to see the veins and get the
              needle into them. It also helps to fill the blood bag more quickly. Next, the skin on the inside of your
              elbow will be cleaned.</li>
            <li><i class="bi bi-check"></i>A new, sterile needle is inserted into a vein in your arm. This needle is
              attached to a thin plastic tube and blood bag. Once the needle is in place, you will have to clench your
              fist several times to help the blood flow from the vein. The blood is first collected into tubes for
              testing. After this procedure, the blood is left to fill approximately the half-liter bag. The needle is
              usually left in place for about 10 minutes. After you've finished donating, the needle is removed, a small
              patch is placed in its place, and a bandage is wrapped around your arm.</li>
            <li><i class="bi bi-check"></i>Another popular method of donating blood is apheresis. During apheresis,
              you'll be connected to a machine that can collect and separate different blood components, such as red
              blood cells, plasma and platelets. This process allows more than one blood component to be collected. But
              it takes longer than a normal blood donation, usually up to two hours.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
